<BaseLayout title={title} description={description}>
  <h1>Frequently Asked Questions</h1>
  <h2>What is &ldquo;protected activity&rdquo;?</h2>
  <p>Activity protected from retaliation includes: filing or supporting a discrimination complaint (EEOC charge, internal HR complaint); reporting wage theft or overtime violations; filing a workers&rsquo; compensation claim; reporting workplace safety violations to OSHA; participating in a government investigation; and refusing to follow an employer&rsquo;s instruction to engage in illegal conduct.</p>
  <h2>How close in time does the firing have to be to the protected activity?</h2>
  <p>There is no legal requirement, but temporal proximity (being fired within days or weeks of protected activity) creates a strong inference of retaliation. Courts have found retaliation even with several months between events when other evidence supports it. The longer the gap, the more additional evidence you need.</p>
  <h2>My employer says I was fired for performance — how do I counter that?</h2>
  <p>Pretext evidence: positive performance reviews before the protected activity; the same performance issues existed before and were tolerated; similarly situated employees who didn&rsquo;t engage in protected activity and had similar performance weren&rsquo;t fired; timing of the termination relative to the complaint.</p>
  <h2>Do I have to file with the EEOC before suing?</h2>
  <p>For Title VII, ADA, ADEA, and GINA retaliation claims: yes, EEOC charge required first. For FLSA retaliation: no EEOC exhaustion required — file directly in court within 2 years. For OSHA retaliation: file with OSHA within 30 days (extremely short!). Workers&rsquo; comp retaliation varies by state.</p>
  <h2>What if I&rsquo;m still employed — can I claim retaliation?</h2>
  <p>Yes. Demotion, pay cuts, removal from desirable assignments, increased scrutiny, and hostile treatment after protected activity are all forms of retaliation even without termination. The Supreme Court held in <em>Burlington Northern v. White</em> (2006) that the retaliation standard covers any materially adverse action that would dissuade a reasonable employee from making a charge.</p>
</BaseLayout>
